# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lightgbm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called **classification trees**; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called **regression trees**.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] More generally, the concept of regression tree can be extended to any kind of object equipped with pairwise dissimilarities such as categorical sequences.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Decision trees are among the most popular machine learning algorithms given their intelligibility and simplicity because they produce algorithms that are easy to interpret and visualize, even for users without a statistical background.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In data mining, a decision tree describes data (but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision making).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Decision tree learning is a method commonly used in data mining.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The goal is to create an algorithm that predicts the value of a target variable based on several input variables.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A decision tree is a simple representation for classifying examples.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For this section, assume that all of the input features have finite discrete domains, and there is a single target feature called the "classification".
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Each element of the domain of the classification is called a *class*.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A decision tree or a classification tree is a tree in which each internal (non-leaf) node is labeled with an input feature.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The arcs coming from a node labeled with an input feature are labeled with each of the possible values of the target feature or the arc leads to a subordinate decision node on a different input feature.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A tree is built by splitting the source set, constituting the root node of the tree, into subsets—which constitute the successor children.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The splitting is based on a set of splitting rules based on classification features.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This process is repeated on each derived subset in a recursive manner called recursive partitioning.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The recursion is completed when the subset at a node has all the same values of the target variable, or when splitting no longer adds value to the predictions.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This process of *top-down induction of decision trees* (TDIDT) is an example of a greedy algorithm, and it is by far the most common strategy for learning decision trees from data.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In data mining, decision trees can be described also as the combination of mathematical and computational techniques to aid the description, categorization and generalization of a given set of data.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The dependent variable, Y , is the target variable that we are trying to understand, classify or generalize.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The vector ${\textbf {x}}$ is composed of the features, $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}$ etc., that are used for that task.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The term **classification and regression tree (CART)** analysis is an umbrella term used to refer to either of the above procedures, first introduced by Breiman et al.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Trees used for regression and trees used for classification have some similarities – but also some differences, such as the procedure used to determine where to split.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A special case of a decision tree is a decision list, which is a one-sided decision tree, so that every internal node has exactly 1 leaf node and exactly 1 internal node as a child (except for the bottommost node, whose only child is a single leaf node).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] While less expressive, decision lists are arguably easier to understand than general decision trees due to their added sparsity, permit non-greedy learning methods and monotonic constraints to be imposed.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] ID3 and CART were invented independently at around the same time (between 1970 and 1980), yet follow a similar approach for learning a decision tree from training tuples.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] It has also been proposed to leverage concepts of fuzzy set theory for the definition of a special version of decision tree, known as Fuzzy Decision Tree (FDT).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In this type of fuzzy classification, generally, an input vector ${\textbf {x}}$ is associated with multiple classes, each with a different confidence value.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Boosted ensembles of FDTs have been recently investigated as well, and they have shown performances comparable to those of other very efficient fuzzy classifiers.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Algorithms for constructing decision trees usually work top-down, by choosing a variable at each step that best splits the set of items.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Different algorithms use different metrics for measuring "best".
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] These generally measure the homogeneity of the target variable within the subsets.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] These metrics are applied to each candidate subset, and the resulting values are combined (e.g., averaged) to provide a measure of the quality of the split.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Depending on the underlying metric, the performance of various heuristic algorithms for decision tree learning may vary significantly.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A simple and effective metric can be used to identify the degree to which true positives outweigh false positives (see Confusion matrix).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In this equation, the total false positives (FP) are subtracted from the total true positives (TP).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The resulting number gives an estimate on how many positive examples the feature could correctly identify within the data, with higher numbers meaning that the feature could correctly classify more positive samples.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Here we can see that the TP value would be 8 and the FP value would be 2 (the underlined numbers in the table).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] When we plug these numbers in the equation we are able to calculate the estimate: $E_{p}=TP-FP=8-2=6$ .
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This means that using the estimate on this feature would have it receive a score of 6.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] However, it should be worth noting that this number is only an estimate.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For example, if two features both had a FP value of 2 while one of the features had a higher TP value, that feature would be ranked higher than the other because the resulting estimate when using the equation would give a higher value.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This could lead to some inaccuracies when using the metric if some features have more positive samples than others.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To combat this, one could use a more powerful metric known as Sensitivity that takes into account the proportions of the values from the confusion matrix to give the actual true positive rate (TPR).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In this example, Feature A had an estimate of 6 and a TPR of approximately 0.73 while Feature B had an estimate of 4 and a TPR of 0.75.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This shows that although the positive estimate for some feature may be higher, the more accurate TPR value for that feature may be lower when compared to other features that have a lower positive estimate.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Depending on the situation and knowledge of the data and decision trees, one may opt to use the positive estimate for a quick and easy solution to their problem.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] On the other hand, a more experienced user would most likely prefer to use the TPR value to rank the features because it takes into account the proportions of the data and all the samples that should have been classified as positive.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For a set of items with J classes and relative frequencies $p_{i}$ , $i\in \{1,2,...,J\}$ , the probability of choosing an item with label i is $p_{i}$ , and the probability of miscategorizing that item is $\sum _{k\neq i}p_{k}=1-p_{i}$ .
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The Gini impurity is also an information theoretic measure and corresponds to Tsallis Entropy with deformation coefficient $q=2$ , which in physics is associated with the lack of information in out-of-equilibrium, non-extensive, dissipative and quantum systems.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For the limit $q\to 1$ one recovers the usual Boltzmann-Gibbs or Shannon entropy.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In this sense, the Gini impurity is nothing but a variation of the usual entropy measure for decision trees.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Used by the ID3, C4.5 and C5.0 tree-generation algorithms, information gain is based on the concept of entropy and information content from information theory.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] where $p_{1},p_{2},\ldots$ are fractions that add up to 1 and represent the percentage of each class present in the child node that results from a split in the tree.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] That is, the expected information gain is the mutual information, meaning that on average, the reduction in the entropy of *T* is the mutual information.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Information gain is used to decide which feature to split on at each step in building the tree.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Simplicity is best, so we want to keep our tree small.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To do so, at each step we should choose the split that results in the most consistent child nodes.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] A commonly used measure of consistency is called information which is measured in bits.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For each node of the tree, the information value "represents the expected amount of information that would be needed to specify whether a new instance should be classified yes or no, given that the example reached that node".
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Consider an example data set with four attributes: *outlook* (sunny, overcast, rainy), *temperature* (hot, mild, cool), *humidity* (high, normal), and *windy* (true, false), with a binary (yes or no) target variable, *play*, and 14 data points.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To construct a decision tree on this data, we need to compare the information gain of each of four trees, each split on one of the four features.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The split with the highest information gain will be taken as the first split and the process will continue until all child nodes each have consistent data, or until the information gain is 0.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To find the information gain of the split using *windy*, we must first calculate the information in the data before the split.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The original data contained nine yes's and five no's.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The split using the feature *windy* results in two child nodes, one for a *windy* value of true and one for a *windy* value of false.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In this data set, there are six data points with a true *windy* value, three of which have a *play* (where *play* is the target variable) value of yes and three with a *play* value of no.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The eight remaining data points with a *windy* value of false contain two no's and six yes's.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The information of the *windy*=true node is calculated using the entropy equation above.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] For the node where *windy*=false there were eight data points, six yes's and two no's.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To find the information of the split, we take the weighted average of these two numbers based on how many observations fell into which node.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Now we can calculate the information gain achieved by splitting on the *windy* feature.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To build the tree, the information gain of each possible first split would need to be calculated.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The best first split is the one that provides the most information gain.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This process is repeated for each impure node until the tree is complete.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This example is adapted from the example appearing in Witten et al.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Information gain is also known as Shannon index in bio diversity research.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Introduced in CART, variance reduction is often employed in cases where the target variable is continuous (regression tree), meaning that use of many other metrics would first require discretization before being applied.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] where S , $S_{t}$ , and $S_{f}$ are the set of presplit sample indices, set of sample indices for which the split test is true, and set of sample indices for which the split test is false, respectively.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Each of the above summands are indeed variance estimates, though, written in a form without directly referring to the mean.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] By replacing $(y_{i}-y_{j})^{2}$ in the formula above with the dissimilarity $d_{ij}$ between two objects i and j , the variance reduction criterion applies to any kind of object for which pairwise dissimilarities can be computed.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Used by CART in 1984, the measure of "goodness" is a function that seeks to optimize the balance of a candidate split's capacity to create pure children with its capacity to create equally-sized children.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Consider an example data set with three attributes: *savings*(low, medium, high), *assets*(low, medium, high), *income*(numerical value), and a binary target variable *credit risk*(good, bad) and 8 data points.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The full data is presented in the table below.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To start a decision tree, we will calculate the maximum value of $\varphi (s\mid t)$ using each feature to find which one will split the root node.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] This process will continue until all children are pure or all $\varphi (s\mid t)$ values are below a set threshold.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To find $\varphi (s\mid t)$ of the feature *savings*, we need to note the quantity of each value.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The original data contained three low's, three medium's, and two high's.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Out of the low's, one had a good *credit risk* while out of the medium's and high's, 4 had a good *credit risk*.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Assume a candidate split s such that records with a low *savings* will be put in the left child and all other records will be put into the right child.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] To build the tree, the "goodness" of all candidate splits for the root node need to be calculated.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The candidate with the maximum value will split the root node, and the process will continue for each impure node until the tree is complete.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Compared to other metrics such as information gain, the measure of "goodness" will attempt to create a more balanced tree, leading to more-consistent decision time.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] However, it sacrifices some priority for creating pure children which can lead to additional splits that are not present with other metrics.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Many data mining software packages provide implementations of one or more decision tree algorithms (e.g. random forest).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In a decision tree, all paths from the root node to the leaf node proceed by way of conjunction, or *AND*.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In a decision graph, it is possible to use disjunctions (ORs) to join two more paths together using minimum message length (MML).
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Decision graphs have been further extended to allow for previously unstated new attributes to be learnt dynamically and used at different places within the graph.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The more general coding scheme results in better predictive accuracy and log-loss probabilistic scoring.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] In general, decision graphs infer models with fewer leaves than decision trees.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Evolutionary algorithms have been used to avoid local optimal decisions and search the decision tree space with little *a priori* bias.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] It is also possible for a tree to be sampled using MCMC.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] The tree can be searched for in a bottom-up fashion.
[src:lightgbm/decision-tree-learning] Or several trees can be constructed parallelly to reduce the expected number of tests till classification.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In statistics and machine learning, **ensemble methods** use multiple learning algorithms to obtain better predictive performance than could be obtained from any of the constituent learning algorithms alone.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Unlike a statistical ensemble in statistical mechanics, which is usually infinite, a machine learning ensemble consists of only a concrete finite set of alternative models, but typically allows for much more flexible structure to exist among those alternatives.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Supervised learning algorithms search through a hypothesis space to find a suitable hypothesis that will make good predictions with a particular problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Even if this space contains hypotheses that are very well-suited for a particular problem, it may be very difficult to find a good one.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensembles combine multiple hypotheses to form one which should be theoretically better.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning typically refers to bagging (bootstrap aggregating), boosting or stacking/blending techniques to induce high variance among the base models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Bagging creates diversity by generating random samples from the training observations and fitting the same model to each different sample — also known as *homogeneous parallel ensembles*.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Boosting follows an iterative process by sequentially training each base model on the up-weighted errors of the previous base model, producing an additive model to reduce the final model errors — also known as *sequential ensemble learning*.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Stacking or blending consists of different base models, each trained independently (i.e. diverse/high variance) to be combined into the ensemble model — producing a *heterogeneous parallel ensemble*.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Common applications of ensemble learning include random forests (an extension of bagging), Boosted Tree models, and Gradient Boosted Tree Models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Models in applications of stacking are generally more task-specific — such as combining clustering techniques with other parametric and/or non-parametric techniques.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Evaluating the prediction of an ensemble typically requires more computation than evaluating the prediction of a single model.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In one sense, ensemble learning may be thought of as a way to compensate for poor learning algorithms by performing a lot of extra computation.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, the alternative is to do a lot more learning with one non-ensemble model.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] An ensemble may be more efficient at improving overall accuracy for the same increase in compute, storage, or communication resources by using that increase on two or more methods, than would have been improved by increasing resource use for a single method.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Fast algorithms such as decision trees are commonly used in ensemble methods (e.g., random forests), although slower algorithms can benefit from ensemble techniques as well.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] By analogy, ensemble techniques have been used also in unsupervised learning scenarios, for example in consensus clustering or in anomaly detection.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Empirically, ensembles tend to yield better results when there is a significant diversity among the models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Many ensemble methods, therefore, seek to promote diversity among the models they combine.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Although perhaps non-intuitive, more random algorithms (like random decision trees) can be used to produce a stronger ensemble than very deliberate algorithms (like entropy-reducing decision trees).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Using a variety of strong learning algorithms, however, has been shown to be more effective than using techniques that attempt to *dumb-down* the models in order to promote diversity.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It is possible to increase diversity in the training stage of the model using correlation for regression tasks or using information measures such as cross entropy for classification tasks.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Theoretically, one can justify the diversity concept because the lower bound of the error rate of an ensemble system can be decomposed into accuracy, diversity, and the other term.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning, including both regression and classification tasks, can be explained using a geometric framework.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Within this framework, the output of each individual classifier or regressor for the entire dataset can be viewed as a point in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The Euclidean distance is used as the metric to measure both the performance of a single classifier or regressor (the distance between its point and the ideal point) and the dissimilarity between two classifiers or regressors (the distance between their respective points).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] This perspective transforms ensemble learning into a deterministic problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] For example, within this geometric framework, it can be proved that the averaging of the outputs (scores) of all base classifiers or regressors can lead to equal or better results than the average of all the individual models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It can also be proved that if the optimal weighting scheme is used, then a weighted averaging approach can outperform any of the individual classifiers or regressors that make up the ensemble or as good as the best performer at least.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] While the number of component classifiers of an ensemble has a great impact on the accuracy of prediction, there is a limited number of studies addressing this problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] *A priori* determining of ensemble size and the volume and velocity of big data streams make this even more crucial for online ensemble classifiers.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Mostly statistical tests were used for determining the proper number of components.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] More recently, a theoretical framework suggested that there is an ideal number of component classifiers for an ensemble such that having more or less than this number of classifiers would deteriorate the accuracy.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It is called "the law of diminishing returns in ensemble construction." Their theoretical framework shows that using the same number of independent component classifiers as class labels gives the highest accuracy.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The Bayes optimal classifier is a classification technique.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It is an ensemble of all the hypotheses in the hypothesis space.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] On average, no other ensemble can outperform it.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The Naive Bayes classifier is a version of this that assumes that the data is conditionally independent on the class and makes the computation more feasible.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Each hypothesis is given a vote proportional to the likelihood that the training dataset would be sampled from a system if that hypothesis were true.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] To facilitate training data of finite size, the vote of each hypothesis is also multiplied by the prior probability of that hypothesis.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] where y is the predicted class, C is the set of all possible classes, H is the hypothesis space, P refers to a *probability*, and T is the training data.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] As an ensemble, the Bayes optimal classifier represents a hypothesis that is not necessarily in H .
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The hypothesis represented by the Bayes optimal classifier, however, is the optimal hypothesis in *ensemble space* (the space of all possible ensembles consisting only of hypotheses in H ).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Bootstrap aggregation (*bagging*) involves training an ensemble on *bootstrapped* data sets.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] A bootstrapped set is created by selecting from original training data set with replacement.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Thus, a bootstrap set may contain a given example zero, one, or multiple times.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble members can also have limits on the features (e.g., nodes of a decision tree), to encourage exploring of diverse features.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The variance of local information in the bootstrap sets and feature considerations promote diversity in the ensemble, and can strengthen the ensemble.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] To reduce overfitting, a member can be validated using the out-of-bag set (the examples that are not in its bootstrap set).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Inference is done by **voting** of predictions of ensemble members, called **aggregation**.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It is illustrated below with an ensemble of four decision trees.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The query example is classified by each tree.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Because three of the four predict the *positive* class, the ensemble's overall classification is *positive*.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Random forests like the one shown are a common application of bagging.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Boosting involves training successive models by emphasizing training data mis-classified by previously learned models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Initially, all data (D1) has equal weight and is used to learn a base model M1.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The examples mis-classified by M1 are assigned a weight greater than correctly classified examples.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] This boosted data (D2) is used to train a second base model M2, and so on.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In some cases, boosting has yielded better accuracy than bagging, but tends to over-fit more.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The most common implementation of boosting is Adaboost, but some newer algorithms are reported to achieve better results.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model averaging (BMA) makes predictions by averaging the predictions of models weighted by their posterior probabilities given the data.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] BMA is known to generally give better answers than a single model, obtained, e.g., via stepwise regression, especially where very different models have nearly identical performance in the training set but may otherwise perform quite differently.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The question with any use of Bayes' theorem is the prior, i.e., the probability (perhaps subjective) that each model is the best to use for a given purpose.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Conceptually, BMA can be used with any prior.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] *R* packages ensembleBMA and BMA use the prior implied by the Bayesian information criterion, (BIC), following Raftery (1995).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] *R* package BAS supports the use of the priors implied by Akaike information criterion (AIC) and other criteria over the alternative models as well as priors over the coefficients.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The difference between BIC and AIC is the strength of preference for parsimony.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] BIC's penalty for model complexity is $\ln(n)k$ , while AIC's is $2k$ .
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] On the other hand, AIC and AICc are asymptotically "efficient" (i.e., minimum mean square prediction error), while BIC is not .
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] (1994) showed that when BMA is used for classification, its expected error is at most twice the expected error of the Bayes optimal classifier.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Burnham and Anderson (1998, 2002) contributed greatly to introducing a wider audience to the basic ideas of Bayesian model averaging and popularizing the methodology.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The availability of software, including other free open-source packages for R beyond those mentioned above, helped make the methods accessible to a wider audience.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Bayesian model combination (BMC) is an algorithmic correction to Bayesian model averaging (BMA).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Instead of sampling each model in the ensemble individually, it samples from the space of possible ensembles (with model weights drawn randomly from a Dirichlet distribution having uniform parameters).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] This modification overcomes the tendency of BMA to converge toward giving all the weight to a single model.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Although BMC is somewhat more computationally expensive than BMA, it tends to yield dramatically better results.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] BMC has been shown to be better on average (with statistical significance) than BMA and bagging.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Use of Bayes' law to compute model weights requires computing the probability of the data given each model.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Typically, none of the models in the ensemble are exactly the distribution from which the training data were generated, so all of them correctly receive a value close to zero for this term.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] This would work well if the ensemble were big enough to sample the entire model-space, but this is rarely possible.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Consequently, each pattern in the training data will cause the ensemble weight to shift toward the model in the ensemble that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It essentially reduces to an unnecessarily complex method for doing model selection.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The possible weightings for an ensemble can be visualized as lying on a simplex.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] At each vertex of the simplex, all of the weight is given to a single model in the ensemble.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] BMA converges toward the vertex that is closest to the distribution of the training data.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] By contrast, BMC converges toward the point where this distribution projects onto the simplex.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In other words, instead of selecting the one model that is closest to the generating distribution, it seeks the combination of models that is closest to the generating distribution.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The results from BMA can often be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best model from a bucket of models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Likewise, the results from BMC may be approximated by using cross-validation to select the best ensemble combination from a random sampling of possible weightings.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] A "bucket of models" is an ensemble technique in which a model selection algorithm is used to choose the best model for each problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] When tested with only one problem, a bucket of models can produce no better results than the best model in the set, but when evaluated across many problems, it will typically produce much better results, on average, than any model in the set.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The most common approach used for model-selection is cross-validation selection (sometimes called a "bake-off contest").
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Cross-Validation Selection can be summed up as: "try them all with the training set, and pick the one that works best".
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Gating is a generalization of Cross-Validation Selection.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It involves training another learning model to decide which of the models in the bucket is best-suited to solve the problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Often, a perceptron is used for the gating model.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It can be used to pick the "best" model, or it can be used to give a linear weight to the predictions from each model in the bucket.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] When a bucket of models is used with a large set of problems, it may be desirable to avoid training some of the models that take a long time to train.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Landmark learning is a meta-learning approach that seeks to solve this problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It involves training only the fast (but imprecise) algorithms in the bucket, and then using the performance of these algorithms to help determine which slow (but accurate) algorithm is most likely to do best.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The most common approach for training classifier is using Cross-entropy cost function.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] However, one would like to train an ensemble of models that have diversity so when we combine them it would provide best results.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Assuming we use a simple ensemble of averaging K classifiers.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] where $e^{k}$ is the cost function of the $k^{th}$ classifier, $q^{k}$ is the probability of the $k^{th}$ classifier, p is the true probability that we need to estimate and $\lambda$ is a parameter between 0 and 1 that define the diversity that we would like to establish.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] When $\lambda =0$ we want each classifier to do its best regardless of the ensemble and when $\lambda =1$ we would like the classifier to be as diverse as possible.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Stacking (sometimes called *stacked generalization*) involves training a model to combine the predictions of several other learning algorithms.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] If an arbitrary combiner algorithm is used, then stacking can theoretically represent any of the ensemble techniques described in this article, although, in practice, a logistic regression model is often used as the combiner.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Stacking typically yields performance better than any single one of the trained models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It has been successfully used on both supervised learning tasks (regression, classification and distance learning ) and unsupervised learning (density estimation).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It has also been used to estimate bagging's error rate.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It has been reported to out-perform Bayesian model-averaging.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The two top-performers in the Netflix competition utilized blending, which may be considered a form of stacking.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Bayesian predictive stacking generalizes the idea of stacking from the statistical estimation literature to the combination of posterior predictive distributions.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] These ideas have also been developed and investigated for Gaussian process models, especially for spatial data analysis and can be used to construct transfer learning frameworks for massive spatial data sets.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Weighted majority algorithm (machine learning).
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In recent years, due to growing computational power, which allows for training in large ensemble learning in a reasonable time frame, the number of ensemble learning applications has grown increasingly.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Land cover mapping is one of the major applications of Earth observation satellite sensors, using remote sensing and geospatial data, to identify the materials and objects which are located on the surface of target areas.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Generally, the classes of target materials include roads, buildings, rivers, lakes, and vegetation.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Some different ensemble learning approaches based on artificial neural networks, kernel principal component analysis (KPCA), decision trees with boosting, random forest and automatic design of multiple classifier systems, are proposed to efficiently identify land cover objects.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Change detection is an image analysis problem, consisting of the identification of places where the land cover has changed over time.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Change detection is widely used in fields such as urban growth, forest and vegetation dynamics, land use and disaster monitoring.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The earliest applications of ensemble classifiers in change detection are designed with the majority voting, Bayesian model averaging, and the maximum posterior probability.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Given the growth of satellite data over time, the past decade sees more use of time series methods for continuous change detection from image stacks.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] One example is a Bayesian ensemble changepoint detection method called BEAST, with the software available as a package Rbeast in R, Python, and Matlab.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Distributed denial of service is one of the most threatening cyber-attacks that may happen to an internet service provider.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] By combining the output of single classifiers, ensemble classifiers reduce the total error of detecting and discriminating such attacks from legitimate flash crowds.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Classification of malware codes such as computer viruses, computer worms, trojans, ransomware and spywares with the usage of machine learning techniques, is inspired by the document categorization problem.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning systems have shown a proper efficacy in this area.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Malware detection models, like all machine learning models, are vulnerable to adversarial machine learning attacks where an attacker pushes the boundary of what is classified as malware.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] By rotating through an ensemble of models using moving target defense, the attacker has a diminished knowledge advantage.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] An intrusion detection system monitors computer network or computer systems to identify intruder codes like an anomaly detection process.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning successfully aids such monitoring systems to reduce their total error.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Face recognition, which recently has become one of the most popular research areas of pattern recognition, copes with identification or verification of a person by their digital images.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Hierarchical ensembles based on Gabor Fisher classifier and independent component analysis preprocessing techniques are some of the earliest ensembles employed in this field.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] It is also being successfully used in facial emotion recognition.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Fraud detection deals with the identification of bank fraud, such as money laundering, credit card fraud and telecommunication fraud, which have vast domains of research and applications of machine learning.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Because ensemble learning improves the robustness of the normal behavior modelling, it has been proposed as an efficient technique to detect such fraudulent cases and activities in banking and credit card systems.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble learning methods have been widely adopted in finance for tasks such as credit scoring, bankruptcy prediction, and risk management.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] By combining multiple base models, ensembles can exploit nonlinear relationships, handle high-dimensional and noisy data, and often deliver more stable out-of-sample performance than single models or traditional statistical baselines such as logistic regression and linear factor models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] This approach aligns with the broader trend in financial machine learning described by Marcos López de Prado, who argues that combining diverse learners can improve robustness, mitigate overfitting, and extract persistent patterns from noisy financial time series.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] In retail and corporate credit scoring, ensemble classifiers such as random forests, gradient boosting machines and stacked models are frequently used to assess default risk.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble methods have also been applied to corporate failure and bankruptcy prediction.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Studies comparing different ensemble constructions (such as bagging, boosting and heterogeneous classifier pools) report that well-tuned ensembles tend to achieve higher classification accuracy and more robust performance across industries than individual models.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] The accuracy of prediction of business failure is a very crucial issue in financial decision-making.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Therefore, different ensemble classifiers are proposed to predict financial crises and financial distress.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Also, in the trade-based manipulation problem, where traders attempt to manipulate stock prices by buying and selling activities, ensemble classifiers are required to analyze the changes in the stock market data and detect suspicious symptom of stock price manipulation.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Implementation of ensemble learning not only with machine learning models but also with mathematical frameworks such as hidden Markov models for applications in trading, regime detection, and asset pricing remains a rapidly developing area of research.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Ensemble classifiers have been successfully applied in neuroscience, proteomics and medical diagnosis like in neuro-cognitive disorder (i.e.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Alzheimer or myotonic dystrophy) detection based on MRI datasets, cervical cytology classification.
[src:lightgbm/ensemble-learning] Besides, ensembles have been successfully applied in medical segmentation tasks, for example brain tumor and hyperintensities segmentation.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In machine learning and pattern recognition, a **feature** is an individual measurable property or characteristic of a data set.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Choosing informative, discriminating, and independent features is crucial to producing effective algorithms for pattern recognition, classification, and regression tasks.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Features are usually numeric, but other types such as strings and graphs are used in syntactic pattern recognition, after some pre-processing step such as one-hot encoding.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] The concept of "features" is related to that of explanatory variables used in statistical techniques such as linear regression.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In feature engineering, two types of features are commonly used: numerical and categorical.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Numerical features are continuous values that can be measured on a scale.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Examples of numerical features include age, height, weight, and income.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Numerical features can be used in machine learning algorithms directly.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Categorical features are discrete values that can be grouped into categories.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Examples of categorical features include gender, color, and zip code.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Categorical features typically need to be converted to numerical features before they can be used in machine learning algorithms.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] This can be done using a variety of techniques, such as one-hot encoding, label encoding, and ordinal encoding.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] The type of feature that is used in feature engineering depends on the specific machine learning algorithm that is being used.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Some machine learning algorithms, such as decision trees, can handle both numerical and categorical features.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Other machine learning algorithms, such as linear regression, can only handle numerical features.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] A numeric feature can be conveniently described by a feature vector.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] One way to achieve binary classification is using a linear predictor function (related to the perceptron) with a feature vector as input.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] The method consists of calculating the scalar product between the feature vector and a vector of weights, qualifying those observations whose result exceeds a threshold.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Algorithms for classification from a feature vector include nearest neighbor classification, neural networks, and statistical techniques such as Bayesian approaches.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In character recognition, features may include histograms counting the number of black pixels along horizontal and vertical directions, number of internal holes, stroke detection and many others.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In speech recognition, features for recognizing phonemes can include noise ratios, length of sounds, relative power, filter matches, logarithmic Mel-scale spectral vectors and Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients, which represent the frequency characteristics of audio signals.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In spam detection algorithms, features may include the presence or absence of certain email headers, the email structure, the language, the frequency of specific terms, the grammatical correctness of the text.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In computer vision, there are a large number of possible features, such as edges and objects.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In pattern recognition and machine learning, a **feature vector** is an n-dimensional vector of numerical features that represent some object.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Many algorithms in machine learning require a numerical representation of objects, since such representations facilitate processing and statistical analysis.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] When representing images, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image, while when representing texts the features might be the frequencies of occurrence of textual terms.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Feature vectors are equivalent to the vectors of explanatory variables used in statistical procedures such as linear regression.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Feature vectors are often combined with weights using a dot product in order to construct a linear predictor function that is used to determine a score for making a prediction.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] The vector space associated with these vectors is often called the **feature space**.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] In order to reduce the dimensionality of the feature space, a number of dimensionality reduction techniques can be employed.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Higher-level features can be obtained from already available features and added to the feature vector; for example, for the study of diseases the feature 'Age' is useful and is defined as *Age = 'Year of death' minus 'Year of birth'*.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] This process is referred to as **feature construction**.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Feature construction is the application of a set of constructive operators to a set of existing features resulting in construction of new features.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Feature construction has long been considered a powerful tool for increasing both accuracy and understanding of structure, particularly in high-dimensional problems.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Applications include studies of disease and emotion recognition from speech.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] The initial set of raw features can be redundant and large enough that estimation and optimization is made difficult or ineffective.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Therefore, a preliminary step in many applications of machine learning and pattern recognition consists of selecting a subset of features, or constructing a new and reduced set of features to facilitate learning, and to improve generalization and interpretability.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Extracting or selecting features is a combination of art and science; developing systems to do so is known as feature engineering.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] It requires the experimentation of multiple possibilities and the combination of automated techniques with the intuition and knowledge of the domain expert.
[src:lightgbm/feature-machine-learning] Automating this process is feature learning, where a machine not only uses features for learning, but learns the features itself.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The idea of gradient boosting originated in the observation by Leo Breiman that boosting can be interpreted as an optimization algorithm on a suitable cost function.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Explicit regression gradient boosting algorithms were subsequently developed, by Jerome H.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman, (in 1999 and later in 2001) simultaneously with the more general functional gradient boosting perspective of Llew Mason, Jonathan Baxter, Peter Bartlett and Marcus Frean.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The latter two papers introduced the view of boosting algorithms as iterative *functional gradient descent* algorithms.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] That is, algorithms that optimize a cost function over function space by iteratively choosing a function (weak hypothesis) that points in the negative gradient direction.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] This functional gradient view of boosting has led to the development of boosting algorithms in many areas of machine learning and statistics beyond regression and classification.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Like other boosting methods, gradient boosting combines weak "learners" into a single strong learner iteratively.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] If the algorithm has M stages, at each stage m ( $1\leq m\leq M$ ), suppose some imperfect model $F_{m}$ (for low m , this model may simply predict ${\hat {y}}_{i}$ to be ${\bar {y}}$ , the mean of y ).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] In order to improve $F_{m}$ , our algorithm should add some new estimator, $h_{m}(x)$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Therefore, gradient boosting will fit $h_{m}$ to the *residual* $y_{i}-F_{m}(x_{i})$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] As in other boosting variants, each $F_{m+1}$ attempts to correct the errors of its predecessor $F_{m}$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] So, gradient boosting could be generalized to a gradient descent algorithm by plugging in a different loss and its gradient.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Many supervised learning problems involve an output variable y and a vector of input variables x, related to each other with some probabilistic distribution.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The goal is to find some function ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that best approximates the output variable from the values of input variables.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The gradient boosting method assumes a real-valued y.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] where $\gamma _{m}$ is the weight at stage m .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] We are usually given a training set $\{(x_{1},y_{1}),\dots ,(x_{n},y_{n})\}$ of known values of x and corresponding values of y.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] In accordance with the empirical risk minimization principle, the method tries to find an approximation ${\hat {F}}(x)$ that minimizes the average value of the loss function on the training set, i.e., minimizes the empirical risk.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] for $m\geq 1$ , where $h_{m}\in {\mathcal {H}}$ is a base learner function.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Unfortunately, choosing the best function $h_{m}$ at each step for an arbitrary loss function L is a computationally infeasible optimization problem in general.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Therefore, we restrict our approach to a simplified version of the problem.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The idea is to apply a steepest descent step to this minimization problem (functional gradient descent).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The basic idea is to find a local minimum of the loss function by iterating on $F_{m-1}(x)$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] In fact, the local maximum-descent direction of the loss function is the negative gradient.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Note that this approach is a heuristic and therefore doesn't yield an exact solution to the given problem, but rather an approximation.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Fit a base learner (or weak learner, e.g. tree) closed under scaling $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals, i.e. train it using the training set $\{(x_{i},r_{im})\}_{i=1}^{n}$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is typically used with decision trees (especially CARTs) of a fixed size as base learners.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] For this special case, Friedman proposes a modification to gradient boosting method which improves the quality of fit of each base learner.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Generic gradient boosting at the *m*-th step would fit a decision tree $h_{m}(x)$ to pseudo-residuals.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Let $J_{m}$ be the number of its leaves.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The tree partitions the input space into $J_{m}$ disjoint regions $R_{1m},\ldots ,R_{J_{m}m}$ and predicts a constant value in each region.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] where $b_{jm}$ is the value predicted in the region $R_{jm}$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman proposes to modify this algorithm so that it chooses a separate optimal value $\gamma _{jm}$ for each of the tree's regions, instead of a single $\gamma _{m}$ for the whole tree.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] He calls the modified algorithm "TreeBoost".
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] When the loss $L(\cdot ,\cdot )$ is mean-squared error (MSE) the coefficients $\gamma _{jm}$ coincide with the coefficients of the tree-fitting procedure $b_{jm}$ .
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The number J of terminal nodes in the trees is a parameter which controls the maximum allowed level of interaction between variables in the model.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] With $J=2$ (decision stumps), no interaction between variables is allowed.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] With $J=3$ the model may include effects of the interaction between up to two variables, and so on.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] J can be adjusted for a data set at hand.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Hastie et al. comment that typically $4\leq J\leq 8$ work well for boosting and results are fairly insensitive to the choice of J in this range, $J=2$ is insufficient for many applications, and $J>10$ is unlikely to be required.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Fitting the training set too closely can lead to degradation of the model's generalization ability, that is, its performance on unseen examples.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Several so-called regularization techniques reduce this overfitting effect by constraining the fitting procedure.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] One natural regularization parameter is the number of gradient boosting iterations *M* (i.e. the number of base models).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Increasing *M* reduces the error on training set, but increases risk of overfitting.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] An optimal value of *M* is often selected by monitoring prediction error on a separate validation data set.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Another regularization parameter for tree boosting is tree depth.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The higher this value the more likely the model will overfit the training data.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] where parameter $\nu$ is called the "learning rate".
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Empirically, it has been found that using small learning rates (such as $\nu <0.1$ ) yields dramatic improvements in models' generalization ability over gradient boosting without shrinking ( $\nu =1$ ).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] However, it comes at the price of increasing computational time both during training and querying: lower learning rate requires more iterations.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Soon after the introduction of gradient boosting, Friedman proposed a minor modification to the algorithm, motivated by Breiman's bootstrap aggregation ("bagging") method.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Specifically, he proposed that at each iteration of the algorithm, a base learner should be fit on a subsample of the training set drawn at random without replacement.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman observed a substantial improvement in gradient boosting's accuracy with this modification.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Subsample size is some constant fraction f of the size of the training set.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] When $f=1$ , the algorithm is deterministic and identical to the one described above.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Smaller values of f introduce randomness into the algorithm and help prevent overfitting, acting as a kind of regularization.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The algorithm also becomes faster, because regression trees have to be fit to smaller datasets at each iteration.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman obtained that $0.5\leq f\leq 0.8$ leads to good results for small and moderate sized training sets.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Therefore, f is typically set to 0.5, meaning that one half of the training set is used to build each base learner.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Also, like in bagging, subsampling allows one to define an out-of-bag error of the prediction performance improvement by evaluating predictions on those observations which were not used in the building of the next base learner.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Out-of-bag estimates help avoid the need for an independent validation dataset, but often underestimate actual performance improvement and the optimal number of iterations.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient tree boosting implementations often also use regularization by limiting the minimum number of observations in trees' terminal nodes.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] It is used in the tree building process by ignoring any splits that lead to nodes containing fewer than this number of training set instances.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Imposing this limit helps to reduce variance in predictions at leaves.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Another useful regularization technique for gradient boosted model is to penalize its complexity.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] For gradient boosted trees, model complexity can be defined as the proportional number of leaves in the trees.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The joint optimization of loss and model complexity corresponds to a post-pruning algorithm to remove branches that fail to reduce the loss by a threshold.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Other kinds of regularization such as an $\ell _{2}$ penalty on the leaf values can also be used to avoid overfitting.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used in the field of learning to rank.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] The commercial web search engines Yahoo and Yandex use variants of gradient boosting in their machine-learned ranking engines.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting is also utilized in High Energy Physics in data analysis.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] At the Large Hadron Collider (LHC), variants of gradient boosting Deep Neural Networks (DNN) were successful in reproducing the results of non-machine learning methods of analysis on datasets used to discover the Higgs boson.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting decision tree was also applied in earth and geological studies – for example quality evaluation of sandstone reservoir.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman introduced his regression technique as a "Gradient Boosting Machine" (GBM).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Mason, Baxter et al. described the generalized abstract class of algorithms as "functional gradient boosting".
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Friedman et al. describe an advancement of gradient boosted models as Multiple Additive Regression Trees (MART); Elith et al. describe that approach as "Boosted Regression Trees" (BRT).
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] A popular open-source implementation for R calls it a "Generalized Boosting Model", however packages expanding this work use BRT.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Yet another name is TreeNet, after an early commercial implementation from Salford System's Dan Steinberg, one of researchers who pioneered the use of tree-based methods.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Gradient boosting can be used for feature importance ranking, which is usually based on aggregating importance function of the base learners.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] For example, if a gradient boosted trees algorithm is developed using entropy-based decision trees, the ensemble algorithm ranks the importance of features based on entropy as well with the caveat that it is averaged out over all base learners.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] While boosting can increase the accuracy of a base learner, such as a decision tree or linear regression, it sacrifices intelligibility and interpretability.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] For example, following the path that a decision tree takes to make its decision is trivial and self-explained, but following the paths of hundreds or thousands of trees is much harder.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] To achieve both performance and interpretability, some model compression techniques allow transforming an XGBoost into a single "born-again" decision tree that approximates the same decision function.
[src:lightgbm/gradient-boosting] Furthermore, its implementation may be more difficult due to the higher computational demand.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] A **histogram** is a visual representation of the distribution of quantitative data.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] To construct a histogram, the first step is to "bin" (or "bucket") the range of values— divide the entire range of values into a series of intervals—and then count how many values fall into each interval.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The bins are usually specified as consecutive, non-overlapping intervals of a variable.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The bins (intervals) are adjacent and are typically (but not required to be) of equal size.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Histograms give a rough sense of the density of the underlying distribution of the data, and often for density estimation: estimating the probability density function of the underlying variable.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The total area of a histogram used for probability density is always normalized to 1.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] If the length of the intervals on the *x*-axis are all 1, then a histogram is identical to a relative frequency plot.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Histograms are sometimes confused with bar charts.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] In a histogram, each bin is for a different range of values, so altogether the histogram illustrates the distribution of values.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] But in a bar chart, each bar is for a different category of observations (e.g., each bar might be for a different population), so altogether the bar chart can be used to compare different categories.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Some authors recommend that bar charts always have gaps between the bars to clarify that they are not histograms.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The term *histogram* was first introduced by Karl Pearson, the founder of mathematical statistics, in lectures delivered in 1892 at University College London.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Pearson's term is sometimes incorrectly said to combine the Greek root γραμμα (*gramma*; 'figure' or 'drawing') with the root ἱστορία (historia; 'inquiry or 'history').
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Alternatively the root ἱστίον (*histion*) is also proposed, meaning 'web' or 'tissue' (as in histology, the study of biological tissue).
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Both of these etymologies are incorrect, and in fact Pearson, who knew Ancient Greek well, derived the term from a different if homophonous Greek root, ἱστός ('something set upright' or 'mast'), referring to the vertical bars in the graph.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Pearson's new term was embedded in a series of other analogous neologisms, such as *stigmogram* and *radiogram*.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Pearson himself noted in 1895 that, although the term *histogram* was new, the type of graph it designates was "a common form of graphical representation".
[src:lightgbm/histogram] In fact the technique of using a bar graph to represent statistical measurements was devised by the Scottish economist, William Playfair, in his *Commercial and political atlas* (1786).
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The words used to describe the patterns in a histogram are: "symmetric", "skewed left" or "right", "unimodal", "bimodal" or "multimodal".
[src:lightgbm/histogram] It is a good idea to plot the data using several different bin widths to learn more about it.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Here is an example on tips given in a restaurant.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Census Bureau found that there were 124 million people who work outside of their homes.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Using their data on the time occupied by travel to work, the table below shows the absolute number of people who responded with travel times "at least 30 but less than 35 minutes" is higher than the numbers for the categories above and below it.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This is likely due to people rounding their reported journey time.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The problem of reporting values as somewhat arbitrarily rounded numbers is a common phenomenon when collecting data from people.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This histogram shows the number of cases per unit interval as the height of each block, so that the area of each block is equal to the number of people in the survey who fall into its category.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The area under the curve represents the total number of cases (124 million).
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This type of histogram shows absolute numbers, with Q in thousands.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This histogram differs from the first only in the vertical scale.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The area of each block is the fraction of the total that each category represents, and the total area of all the bars is equal to 1 (the fraction meaning "all").
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The curve displayed is a simple density estimate.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This version shows proportions, and is also known as a unit area histogram.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] In other words, a histogram represents a frequency distribution by means of rectangles whose widths represent class intervals and whose areas are proportional to the corresponding frequencies: the height of each is the average frequency density for the interval.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The intervals are placed together in order to show that the data represented by the histogram, while exclusive, is also contiguous.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] (E.g., in a histogram it is possible to have two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 20.5–33.5, but not two connecting intervals of 10.5–20.5 and 22.5–32.5.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The data used to construct a histogram are generated via a function *m**i* that counts the number of observations that fall into each of the disjoint categories (known as *bins*).
[src:lightgbm/histogram] A histogram can be thought of as a simplistic kernel density estimation, which uses a kernel to smooth frequencies over the bins.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This yields a smoother probability density function, which will in general more accurately reflect distribution of the underlying variable.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The density estimate could be plotted as an alternative to the histogram, and is usually drawn as a curve rather than a set of boxes.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Histograms are nevertheless preferred in applications, when their statistical properties need to be modeled.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The correlated variation of a kernel density estimate is very difficult to describe mathematically, while it is simple for a histogram where each bin varies independently.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] An alternative to kernel density estimation is the average shifted histogram, which is fast to compute and gives a smooth curve estimate of the density without using kernels.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] A cumulative histogram: a mapping that counts the cumulative number of observations in all of the bins up to the specified bin.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] There is no "best" number of bins, and different bin sizes can reveal different features of the data.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Grouping data is at least as old as Graunt's work in the 17th century, but no systematic guidelines were given until Sturges's work in 1926.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Using wider bins where the density of the underlying data points is low reduces noise due to sampling randomness; using narrower bins where the density is high (so the signal drowns the noise) gives greater precision to the density estimation.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Thus varying the bin-width within a histogram can be beneficial.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Nonetheless, equal-width bins are widely used.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Some theoreticians have attempted to determine an optimal number of bins, but these methods generally make strong assumptions about the shape of the distribution.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Depending on the actual data distribution and the goals of the analysis, different bin widths may be appropriate, so experimentation is usually needed to determine an appropriate width.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] There are, however, various useful guidelines and rules of thumb.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The braces indicate the ceiling function.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] which takes the square root of the number of data points in the sample and rounds to the next integer.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This rule is suggested by a number of elementary statistics textbooks and widely implemented in many software packages.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Sturges's rule is derived from a binomial distribution and implicitly assumes an approximately normal distribution.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Sturges's formula implicitly bases bin sizes on the range of the data, and can perform poorly if *n* < 30, because the number of bins will be small—less than seven—and unlikely to show trends in the data well.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] On the other extreme, Sturges's formula may overestimate bin width for very large datasets, resulting in oversmoothed histograms.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] It may also perform poorly if the data are not normally distributed.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] When compared to Scott's rule and the Terrell-Scott rule, two other widely accepted formulas for histogram bins, the output of Sturges's formula is closest when *n* ≈ 100.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The Rice rule is presented as a simple alternative to Sturges's rule.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Doane's formula is a modification of Sturges's formula which attempts to improve its performance with non-normal data.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] where ${\hat {\sigma }}$ is the sample standard deviation.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Scott's normal reference rule is optimal for random samples of normally distributed data, in the sense that it minimizes the integrated mean squared error of the density estimate.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This is the default rule used in Microsoft Excel.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The Terrell–Scott rule is not a normal reference rule.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] It gives the minimum number of bins required for an asymptotically optimal histogram, where optimality is measured by the integrated mean squared error.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The bound is derived by finding the 'smoothest' possible density, which turns out to be ${\frac {3}{4}}(1-x^{2})$ .
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Any other density will require more bins, hence the above estimate is also referred to as the 'oversmoothed' rule.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The similarity of the formulas and the fact that Terrell and Scott were at Rice University when the proposed it suggests that this is also the origin of the Rice rule.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] which is based on the interquartile range, denoted by IQR.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] It replaces 3.5σ of Scott's rule with 2 IQR, which is less sensitive than the standard deviation to outliers in data.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Here, $N_{k}$ is the number of datapoints in the *k*th bin, and choosing the value of *h* that minimizes *J* will minimize integrated mean squared error.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Rather than choosing evenly spaced bins, for some applications it is preferable to vary the bin width.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] A common case is to choose *equiprobable bins*, where the number of samples in each bin is expected to be approximately equal.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] The bins may be chosen according to some known distribution or may be chosen based on the data so that each bin has $\approx n/k$ samples.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] When plotting the histogram, the *frequency density* is used for the dependent axis.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] While all bins have approximately equal area, the heights of the histogram approximate the density distribution.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This choice of bins is motivated by maximizing the power of a Pearson chi-squared test testing whether the bins do contain equal numbers of samples.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Where $\Phi ^{-1}$ is the probit function.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Following this rule for $\alpha =0.05$ would give between $1.88n^{2/5}$ and $3.77n^{2/5}$ ; the coefficient of 2 is chosen as an easy-to-remember value from this broad optimum.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] A good reason why the number of bins should be proportional to ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ is the following: suppose that the data are obtained as n independent realizations of a bounded probability distribution with smooth density.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Then the histogram remains equally "rugged" as n tends to infinity.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] If s is the "width" of the distribution (e. g., the standard deviation or the inter-quartile range), then the number of units in a bin (the frequency) is of order $nh/s$ and the *relative* standard error is of order ${\sqrt {s/(nh)}}$ .
[src:lightgbm/histogram] Compared to the next bin, the relative change of the frequency is of order $h/s$ provided that the derivative of the density is non-zero.
[src:lightgbm/histogram] These two are of the same order if h is of order $s/{\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ , so that k is of order ${\sqrt[{3}]{n}}$ .
[src:lightgbm/histogram] This simple cubic root choice can also be applied to bins with non-constant widths.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] The LightGBM framework supports different algorithms including GBT, GBDT, GBRT, GBM, MART and RF.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] LightGBM has many of XGBoost's advantages, including sparse optimization, parallel training, multiple loss functions, regularization, bagging, and early stopping.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] A major difference between the two lies in the construction of trees.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] LightGBM does not grow a tree level-wise — row by row — as most other implementations do.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] It will choose the leaf with max delta loss to grow.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] Besides, LightGBM does not use the widely used sorted-based decision tree learning algorithm, which searches the best split point on sorted feature values, as XGBoost or other implementations do.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] Instead, LightGBM implements a highly optimized histogram-based decision tree learning algorithm, which yields great advantages on both efficiency and memory consumption.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] The LightGBM algorithm utilizes two novel techniques called Gradient-Based One-Side Sampling (GOSS) and Exclusive Feature Bundling (EFB) which allow the algorithm to run faster while maintaining a high level of accuracy.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] LightGBM works on Linux, Windows, and macOS and supports C++, Python, R, and C#.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] The source code is licensed under MIT License and available on GitHub.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] When using gradient descent, one thinks about the space of possible configurations of the model as a valley, in which the lowest part of the valley is the model which most closely fits the data.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] In this metaphor, one walks in different directions to learn how much lower the valley becomes.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] Typically, in gradient descent, one uses the whole set of data to calculate the valley's slopes.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] However, this commonly used method assumes that every data point is equally informative.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] By contrast, Gradient-Based One-Side Sampling (GOSS), a method first developed for gradient-boosted decision trees, does not rely on the assumption that all data are equally informative.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] Instead, it treats data points with smaller gradients (shallower slopes) as less informative by randomly dropping them.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] This is intended to filter out data which may have been influenced by noise, allowing the model to more accurately model the underlying relationships in the data.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] Exclusive feature bundling (EFB) is a near-lossless method to reduce the number of effective features.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] In a sparse feature space many features are nearly exclusive, implying they rarely take nonzero values simultaneously.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] One-hot encoded features are a perfect example of exclusive features.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] EFB bundles these features, reducing dimensionality to improve efficiency while maintaining a high level of accuracy.
[src:lightgbm/lightgbm] The bundle of exclusive features into a single feature is called an exclusive feature bundle.
